subsection.p:
Matrix notation gives us a convenient way of representing the 2 \times 2 system. If we let 
            A =
            \begin{pmatrix}
            a & b \\
            c & d
            \end{pmatrix}
            \quad\text{and}\quad
            {\mathbf x}(t)
            =
            \begin{pmatrix}
            x(t) \\ y(t)
            \end{pmatrix},
        then we can rewrite our system as
            \begin{pmatrix}
            x'(t) \\ y'(t)
            \end{pmatrix}
            =
            \begin{pmatrix}
            ax(t) + b y(t) \\ cx(t) + d y(t)
            \end{pmatrix}
            =
            \begin{pmatrix}
            a & b \\
            c & d
            \end{pmatrix}
            \begin{pmatrix}
            x(t) \\ y(t)
            \end{pmatrix}.
        In other words, we can write our system as
            \frac{d \mathbf x}{dt} = A {\mathbf x},
        where
            \mathbf x' = \frac{d \mathbf x}{dt} =  \begin{pmatrix} x'(t) \\ y'(t) \end{pmatrix}.
